        "excerpt": "Is it lawful to do good or to do harm on the Sabbath, to save a life or to kill?",
        "body": "The episode opens with Mark's signature compression. A man with a withered hand is in the synagogue. The Pharisees are watching — the imperfect tense *paretēroun* (3:2) is durative; they have been waiting for this opportunity. They are not interested in whether the man will be healed. They are interested in whether they can prosecute the Healer. The setup is forensic from the first verse.\n\nJesus refuses to perform a hidden healing. He calls the man forward — *into the middle* (*eis to meson*, 3:3) — making the act public and unavoidable. Then He turns the legal question back on His accusers: *Is it lawful to do good or to do harm on the Sabbath, to save a life or to kill?* The question is a moral trap of His own design. There is no orthodox Jewish answer except that doing good is lawful. But the Pharisees cannot say so without losing their case. Mark records the result with one devastating word: *they kept silent* (*esiōpōn*, 3:4). Their silence is the confession that they have abandoned the moral question for the political one.\n\nThe verse that follows (3:5) is one of the most penetrating in the Gospel. Jesus *looks around at them with anger, grieved at their hardness of heart*. The Greek participle *sullupeō* — to be grieved together with — pictures the Lord's heart torn alongside His indignation. Calvin in his *Harmony* observes that Christ's anger here is not the sinful passion of a wounded ego but the holy reflex of a Savior watching men refuse the salvation in front of them. Anger and grief are not contradictory in God; they are the same response to the same evil seen from two sides. The Pharisees' hardness (*pōrōsis*) is the chapter's diagnosis of religious hostility — not ignorance but calcified moral resistance.\n\nThe healing itself is anticlimactic. Jesus speaks; the hand obeys. The drama is not in the miracle but in the verdict the miracle provokes. Verse 6 is one of the most ominous in Mark: *the Pharisees went out and immediately began conspiring with the Herodians against Him, as to how they might destroy Him*. The Pharisees were religious purists who despised Rome; the Herodians were political collaborators with Rome. They were natural enemies. The fact that they ally against Jesus reveals the depth of the threat He poses. From this verse forward, the cross is the destination.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Paratereō* (3:2) is the surveillance verb used of legal observation. *Periblepō* (3:5) — to look around, deliberately — is a distinctive Markan verb of Jesus' searching gaze; it returns at 3:34 to render the opposite verdict on the obedient crowd. *Apokathistēmi* (3:5, *was restored*) is the same verb used in the Septuagint of eschatological restoration (Mal 4:6 LXX) — the hand restored signals the deeper restoration Jesus has come to bring."
