        "excerpt": "Whenever the unclean spirits saw Him, they would fall down before Him and shout, \"You are the Son of God!\"",
        "body": "Jesus withdraws from the synagogue to the sea — a tactical retreat, but also a theological one. The institutional center has rejected Him; the open ground receives Him. Mark catalogs the geographic origins of the crowd with care (3:7-8): Galilee, Judea, Jerusalem, Idumea, beyond the Jordan, Tyre and Sidon. This is a deliberate sweep across Israel's traditional borders, including regions long associated with Gentile presence (Idumea, the Decapolis area, Phoenicia). The Messiah rejected by Israel's leadership is being sought by Israel's full geographic extent and beyond.\n\nThe verb *plēthos* (3:7-8) emphasizes the *number* of people; *ochlos* (3:9) emphasizes the *crowd* as a single pressing mass. The crowd is so dense that Jesus has a boat held ready offshore in case He needs to escape suffocation (3:9). Mark's detail is not incidental — the same crowds whose desperation makes ministry physically impossible are the proof that Jesus' mission is gaining traction precisely as the religious leadership turns to murder.\n\nThe striking verses are 11-12. The unclean spirits — repeatedly, habitually (*hotan*, *whenever*) — fall before Jesus and confess Him as *Son of God*. This is the Gospel's central Christological title, and Mark places it on demonic lips. The demons know who Jesus is; they have known since 1:24. The scribes who will charge Him with demon-possession in 3:22 are theologically inferior to the demons they impute. Mark's irony is sharp.\n\nJesus' response to demonic confession is the strict warning (*epitimaō*, 3:12) not to disclose who He is. This is Mark's so-called *messianic secret* — Jesus refuses public proclamation of His identity until the cross gives that identity its proper content. A Messiah confessed without reference to the cross is a Messiah misunderstood. Even true theology, on demonic lips, will mislead a crowd looking for a political deliverer. The full disclosure of Jesus as Son of God waits for the centurion at the foot of the cross (15:39).\n\n> **Greek note.** *Anachōreō* (3:7) is the tactical withdrawal verb used in Matthew of Jesus retreating before threat — here, retreat from the synagogue to the sea. *Mastix* (3:10, translated *afflictions*) literally means *scourge* or *whip* — the diseases lash the people; touching Jesus is the only relief. *Theōreō* (3:11) for the demons' sight is the verb of careful, perceiving observation — they *recognize* what scribes will not."
