        "number": 4,
        "title": "The strong man bound — the Beelzebul controversy and the unforgivable sin",
        "range": "3:20-30",
        "excerpt": "No one can enter the strong man's house and plunder his property unless he first binds the strong man.",
        "body": "Mark now deploys his most distinctive literary device — the *intercalation* or sandwich. The family episode opens at 3:20-21 with the report that Jesus' relatives have come to *take custody of Him* because they think He has lost His senses (*exestē*, literally *stood outside himself*). The episode is interrupted by the scribes' charge (3:22-30) before being closed in 3:31-35 with the family's arrival. The two outer panels and the middle panel are meant to interpret each other: Jesus' family and Jerusalem's theologians both render the same verdict — He is not in His right mind, He has an unclean spirit. Both are *outside*.\n\nThe scribes' charge in 3:22 is doctrinally clever but morally catastrophic. They cannot deny the exorcisms — the cases are public and undisputed. So they accept the data and attack the source: *He is possessed by Beelzebul* (likely a corruption of *Baal-zebul*, \"lord of the heights,\" or *Baal-zebub*, \"lord of the flies\" — 2 Kings 1:2), and *He casts out the demons by the ruler of the demons*. The argument concedes Jesus' power; it merely reroutes its origin.\n\nJesus' response unfolds in two stages. First, the reductio ad absurdum (3:23-26). If Satan casts out Satan, his kingdom is divided against itself, and a divided kingdom cannot stand. The triple parallel — kingdom (*basileia*), house (*oikia*), Satan (*Satanas*) — drives the point three times for emphasis. If the scribes' charge were true, Satan would already be in collapse, and the exorcisms would only confirm his fall. Either way, Jesus' work is good news.\n\nSecond, the positive thesis (3:27). The strong-man parable reveals what Jesus has actually been doing. Satan is the *ischuros*, the strong man, whose house is full of captives — every demonized soul, every disease-bound body, every sin-shackled sinner. Jesus is the *ischuroteros* (cf. John the Baptist's prediction in 1:7, *one is coming who is mightier than I*) who has entered the house and bound the owner. The exorcisms and healings are not random acts of compassion; they are the systematic plundering of Satan's house. *Diarpazō* (3:27, twice) is the military verb for carrying off spoils after a victory. The kingdom of God is a real territorial advance against a real adversary.\n\nThe warning of 3:28-30 follows directly. *All sins shall be forgiven the sons of men, and whatever blasphemies they utter; but whoever blasphemes against the Holy Spirit never has forgiveness, but is guilty of an eternal sin.* This is the most generous statement about forgiveness in Mark and the most severe warning about its limit, in adjacent verses. The breadth (*all sins, all blasphemies*) is staggering — there is no act so grave that the cross does not cover it. The exception is defined immediately by Mark's editorial gloss in v. 30: *because they were saying, 'He has an unclean spirit.'* The unforgivable sin is the willful, settled attribution of the Spirit's saving work to Satan — a hardened inversion of moral reality. It is not a slip of the tongue, not a moment of doubt, not even a season of unbelief. It is the calcified posture that calls black white because acknowledging white would demand repentance. Edwards in *Religious Affections* and Owen in his treatment of mortification both treat this sin as a settled state of the heart, not an episode of the lips. The pastoral implication is precise: the conscience that fears it has committed this sin almost certainly has not, because the fear itself testifies that the Spirit is still drawing.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Existēmi* (3:21, *He has lost His senses*) literally means *to stand outside oneself* — the same root that gives English *ecstasy*; the family thinks Jesus is in a state of religious mania. *Beelzeboul* (3:22) is preserved untranslated by Mark; the term's etymology is debated but its referent is clear — Satan under a contemptuous Jewish nickname. *Ischuros / ischuroteros* (3:27) — the strong man / the stronger one — picks up John the Baptist's prediction in 1:7, identifying Jesus as the *ischuroteros* who was promised. *Aiōnion hamartēma* (3:29, *eternal sin*) — a sin whose consequences extend into the age to come; not merely a sin that lasts long but a sin whose unforgiveness is unbreakable."
